Module nl.naturalis.common
Package nl.naturalis.common.collection

Class TypeMap<V>

java.lang.Object
nl.naturalis.common.collection.TypeMap<V>
Type Parameters:
V - The type of the values in the Map
All Implemented Interfaces:
Map<Class<?>,V>
Direct Known Subclasses:
LinkedTypeGraphMap, SimpleTypeMap, TypeGraphMap
public abstract sealed class TypeMap<V> extends Object permits TypeGraphMap<V>, LinkedTypeGraphMap<V> (not exhaustive)
Base class for TypeGraphMap, SimpleTypeMap and TypeTreeMap. A TypeMap is a specialized Map implementation used to map types to values. Its main feature is that, if a type requested via get or containsKey is not present in the map, but one of its supertypes is, then it will return the value associated with the supertype. The requested type's class hierarchy takes precedence over its interface hierarchy.

A TypeMap is not modifiable. All map-altering methods throw an UnsupportedOperationException. Neither keys nor values are allowed to be null. If the map contains Object.class, it is guaranteed to always return a non-null value. Note that this is actually a deviation from Java's type hierarchy since primitive types do not extend Object.class. However, the point of the TypeMap class is to provide natural default values for groups of types through their common ancestor, and we want Object.class to be associated with the ultimate, last-resort, fall-back value. The getOrDefault(Object, Object) also throws an UnsupportedOperationException as it sidesteps the TypeMap paradigm.

Autoboxing

A TypeMap can be configured to "autobox" the types requested by the client. That is, if, for example, the client makes a request for double.class, but the map only contains an entry for Double.class, then that is the type being served. If there is no entry for Double.class either, but there is one for Number.class, then that is the type being served. Thus, with autoboxing enabled, you need (and should) only add the wrapper types to the map, unless you want the primitive type to be associated with a different value than the wrapper type.
